mumebuhi wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; I am a newbie using JUnit 4.
&gt; 
&gt; I try to test a method, method_1(), that is defined to throw two
&gt; exceptions (well, one at a time), e.g. Exception_A and Exception_B.
&gt; Thus, my test method looks like:
&gt; 
&gt; ---start---
&gt; @Test (expected = Exception_A.class)
&gt; public void testMethod() throws Exception_A, Exception_B {
&gt; try {
&gt; method_1();
&gt; }
&gt; catch (Exception_A e) { throw e; }
&gt; catch (Exception_B e) { throw e; }
&gt; }
&gt; ---end---
&gt; 
&gt; Is this currently the way to achieve this? Is there a better way?

If the method declares that it throws A and B, there is no need to catch 
them. Remove the try/catch block and see what happens.
